  851: `Double underscore prefix (__) triggers name mangling, making attributes "private" by changing their name. Si class MyClass: def __init__(self): self.__x = 1; obj = MyClass(); obj.__x, alors obj.__x lève an AttributeError car Python automatically renames __x to _MyClass__x (adding the class name prefix). This is name mangling - Python changes the attribute name to include the class name, making it harder to access from outside the class. The attribute still exists, but with a different name (_MyClass__x), so direct access via __x fails.

Mangling de noms with double underscore:
• obj.__x lève AttributeError
• Python renames __x to _MyClass__x
• Mangling de noms adds class name prefix
• Direct access via __x fails
• Lève AttributeError

Comment ça fonctionne :
• self.__x = 1 sets attribute
• Python renames __x to _MyClass__x internally
• obj.__x tries to access __x
• Python looks for __x (not found, it's _MyClass__x now)
• Lève AttributeError: 'MyClass' object has no attribute '__x'

Exemple :
class MyClass:
    def __init__(self):
        self.__x = 1  # Name mangled to _MyClass__x
obj = MyClass()
obj.__x                # AttributeError (name mangled)
obj._MyClass__x       # 1 (mangled name works)

Usages courants :
• Private attributes: self.__attr (name mangled, harder to access)
• Encapsulation: prevent direct access to internal attributes
• Mangling de noms
• Object-oriented programming

Exemple : Si class MyClass: def __init__(self): self.__x = 1; obj = MyClass(); obj.__x, alors obj.__x lève an AttributeError car double underscore prefix triggers name mangling, renaming __x to _MyClass__x.
`,
